=== COMMAND REFERENCE ===
Command: USE [MOCK | "filename[sheet]"] [/FMT=format] [/NSCAN=n]
Loads a dataset from CSV, ODF, or OOXML files into the Data Table.
USE MOCK generates synthetic test data.
Sheet selection (ODF/OOXML only):
  Append the sheet name in brackets inside the filename string.
  The name is case-sensitive and must match the tab label exactly.
  If omitted or not found, the first sheet is used.
  Example:  USE "sales.xlsx[Q2]"
Options:
  /FMT=format  Specifies the file format (CSV, ODF, OOXML).
               Default is auto-detected from file extension.
  /NSCAN=n     Number of rows to scan for type detection (default: 20).
Formula cells (ODF/OOXML):
  sdata has no built-in formula evaluator.
  If LibreOffice (soffice) is on PATH, it is invoked to recalculate
  formulas before import.  Otherwise cached values from the last save
  are used -- correct for normally-saved files, but potentially stale
  for volatile functions (TODAY, NOW, RAND) or manual-recalc files.
Execution: Immediate -- loads the dataset at once.

Command: SAVE "filename[sheet]" [/FMT=format] [/HEADER=YES|NO]
Queues the current Data Table to be saved after the next RUN command.
Sheet selection (ODF/OOXML only):
  Append the sheet name in brackets inside the filename string.
  Default sheet name: "Sheet1".
  Example:  SAVE "results.xlsx[Summary]"
Options:
  /FMT=format  Specifies the output format (CSV, ODF, OOXML).
               Default is auto-detected from file extension.
  /HEADER=val  Whether to write a header row (YES or NO). Default: YES.
Execution: Declarative -- the file is written at the end of the next RUN.

Command: WRITE
Explicitly writes the current PDV record to the output table.
Suppresses the automatic end-of-step write for that record.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: SUBMIT "filename"
Executes commands from an external script file. Default extension: .CMD.
Provides cycle detection to prevent recursive submission.
Disabled by --nosubmit flag.
Execution: Immediate -- the script is run at once.

Command: SYSTEM "command"
Executes an external shell command. Disabled by --noshell.
Uses /bin/sh on POSIX systems to avoid profile script side-effects.
A timeout is applied when OPTIONS SHELLTIMEOUT > 0 (requires timeout(1) on PATH).
If the command exceeds the timeout, Script_Error is raised.
Default timeout: 300 s in batch mode, 0 (unlimited) in interactive mode.
Override at startup with --shell-timeout=N; override at runtime with OPTIONS SHELLTIMEOUT N.
Execution: Immediate -- the shell command is launched at once.

Command: PRINT [expr [[,] | [;] expr] ...]
Outputs values to the console, separated by spaces.
No arguments: Prints all permanent variables for the current record.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: RUN
Triggers the execution of the Data Step and any deferred SAVE operations.
Execution: Immediate -- triggers the data step at once.

Command: LET variable = expression
Creates a permanent column in the table or updates an existing one.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: SET variable = expression
Creates a session variable not written to the output table.
SET variables are not reset between records and persist across RUN calls.
They are removed by UNSET or NEW, or when the session ends.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: UNSET variable(s)
Removes one or more session variables from memory.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: ARRAY array_name variable(s)
Creates a virtual array providing indexed access to existing variables.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: DIM <arrayname> (<lower> [TO <upper>]) [/TEMP]
Creates a permanent or temporary array (real variables).
Elements are initialized to missing. /TEMP makes it temporary.
A DIM statement that references an existing variable or array shall fail.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: BY variable(s)  |  BY
Groups data by the named variables for the next RUN.
Sets BOG/EOG indicators and makes BY-group boundaries visible to
LAG, NEXT, and BOG/EOG functions.
Bare BY (no variables) cancels the active grouping.
Execution: Declarative -- grouping is active for all subsequent RUNs.

Command: SORT variable(s)
Reorders the Data Table based on the specified variables.
Execution: Immediate -- re-orders the table at once.

Command: NEW
Clears the Data Table, all variables, and the queued program.
Also resets the active SELECT record filter and BY grouping.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: LIST
Execution: Immediate
Displays the numbered contents of the program buffer (deferred statements
queued for the next RUN).  If the buffer is empty, reports that fact.
See also: DISPLAY to show Data Table records.
          DELETE n[-m] to remove program buffer entries.

Command: DISPLAY [variable(s)]
Execution: Immediate
Displays the current Data Table as a formatted table.
  DISPLAY         -- show all columns.
  DISPLAY varlist -- show only the named columns.
Respects any active SELECT filter (only visible records are shown).
Column ranges are supported:  DISPLAY A-Z

Command: NAMES
Lists currently defined permanent and temporary variables.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: DELETE
Two forms:
  DELETE           Discard the current record; no output is produced for it.
                   Execution: Deferred -- executed per record in the data step.
  DELETE n[-m]     Remove program buffer entries n through m (1-based).
                   A single number removes one entry; n-m removes a range.
                   Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.
                   Only meaningful in interactive (REPL) mode.

Command: BREAK  |  BREAK WHEN <boolean-expr>
Pauses execution and enters the debug inspection prompt.
Valid only inside a data step (deferred context); ignored in immediate mode.
BREAK always pauses. BREAK WHEN <expr> pauses only when the condition is true.
Examples:
  BREAK                   -- pause on every record
  BREAK WHEN RECNO() = 5  -- pause on record 5 only
  BREAK WHEN SALARY > 100000

When paused, the inspection prompt accepts:
  PRINT <expr>   Evaluate and display any SData expression
  RECORD N       Load record N into the inspection view
  RECORD +N      Advance N records from current inspection position
  RECORD -N      Go back N records from current inspection position
  CONTINUE / C   Resume execution from the paused point
  STEP / S       Resume to the next record, then pause again
  RUN            Resume to completion with no further automatic pausing

In non-interactive mode (stdin not a TTY), BREAK emits a trace line to
stderr and continues automatically without waiting for input.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: HOLD [variable(s)]
Retains the listed permanent variables across records.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: UNHOLD [variable(s)]
Cancels a previous HOLD. No args = unhold all.
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: KEEP variable(s)
Drops all permanent variables NOT listed after the next RUN.
Execution: Declarative -- columns are removed at the end of the next RUN.

Command: DROP variable(s)
Drops the listed permanent variables after the next RUN.
Execution: Declarative -- columns are removed at the end of the next RUN.

Command: RENAME old=new [, old=new ...]
Renames columns in the Data Table.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: IF condition THEN stmt [ELSEIF cond THEN stmt] [ELSE stmt]
Conditional execution. Supports single-line and multi-line block forms.
Example:
  IF AGE < 18 THEN
    LET STATUS$ = "MINOR"
  ELSEIF AGE < 65 THEN
    LET STATUS$ = "ADULT"
  ELSE
    LET STATUS$ = "SENIOR"
  END IF

Also usable as a function: IF(condition, true_value, false_value)
Returns true_value when condition is non-zero/non-empty, else false_value.
Example: LET STATUS$ = IF(AGE < 18, "MINOR", "ADULT")
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

-- Record filter form ----------------------------------------
Command: SELECT expression  |  SELECT /ALL
Activates a virtual record filter for subsequent RUNs.
Only records for which <expression> is true are visible;
RECNO, BOF, EOF, BOG, EOG, LAG, and NEXT all operate within
the filtered (logical) view.  The filter is rebuilt automatically
at the start of every RUN against the current table.
SELECT /ALL cancels the active filter and restores all records.
The filter persists until SELECT /ALL or NEW is executed.
Example:
  select score > 70   -- keep only high scorers
  run
  select /all         -- cancel filter
Execution: Declarative -- filter is active for all subsequent RUNs.

-- Multi-way branch form --------------------------------------
Command: SELECT [expression]
  CASE value : statement
  WHEN condition : statement
  OTHERWISE : statement
END SELECT
Example:
  SELECT GRADE$
    CASE "A" : PRINT "EXCELLENT"
    CASE "B" : PRINT "GOOD"
    OTHERWISE : PRINT "SEE ME"
  END SELECT
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: FOR var = start TO end [STEP s] ... NEXT
Counter-controlled loop.
Example:
  FOR I = 1 TO 10 STEP 2
    PRINT I
  NEXT I
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: WHILE condition ... WEND
Condition-controlled loop; executes while condition is true.
Example:
  SET I = 1
  WHILE I <= 10
    PRINT I
    SET I = I + 1
  WEND
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command (data step): REPEAT n  (creates n records)
Execution: Declarative -- the n-record mode is active for the next RUN.

Command (loop): REPEAT ... UNTIL condition
Post-test loop; always executes the body at least once.
Example:
  SET I = 1
  REPEAT
    PRINT I
    SET I = I + 1
  UNTIL I > 10
Execution: Deferred -- executed once per record inside the data step.

Command: OUTPUT ["filename"] [/CHARSET=...] [/FMT=...]
Redirects all console output to a file (written to file AND stdout).
No arguments: Closes the current output file.
Options:
  /CHARSET=cs  Specifies the character set (e.g., UTF-8, ASCII).
  /FMT=format  Specifies the file format (e.g., CSV, ODF).
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: ECHO ON | OFF
Enables or disables writing console output to stdout.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: DIGITS n
Sets decimal places for floating-point output (default 5).
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: FPATH [path] [/ USE | SAVE | SUBMIT | OUTPUT]
Sets the default directory for the specified command(s).
Execution: Declarative -- applies to all subsequent file commands.

Command: RSEED n
Seeds the random number generator with integer n.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: HELP [topic | /ALL]
Displays help. HELP /ALL prints the full reference.
Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.

Command: QUIT | END
Exits the interpreter.
Execution: Immediate -- exits at once.

Command: OPTIONS [key value]
Sets a runtime option. Execution: Immediate -- takes effect at once.
With no arguments, OPTIONS lists all current option values.

  OPTIONS MAXINTAB n         : Max in-memory table cells (rows*cols; 0 = unlimited)
  OPTIONS MAXTEMPMEM n       : Max temporary variables (0 = unlimited)
  OPTIONS CSVDLM ","|"\t"|";"|"|"  : CSV field delimiter (default: comma)
  OPTIONS HEADER YES|NO      : CSV files have a header row (default: YES)
  OPTIONS SAVEOVERWRT YES|NO : Overwrite existing files on SAVE (default: YES)
  OPTIONS TXTFMT AUTO|LF|CRLF|CR  : Line ending for CSV output (default: AUTO)
  OPTIONS CHARSET name       : Character set label (stored, advisory only)
  OPTIONS IEEE_DIVIDE YES|NO : Float /0 -> +/-Inf instead of error (default: NO)
                               0.0/0.0 always raises an error. Cleared by NEW.
  OPTIONS SHELLTIMEOUT n     : SYSTEM/SHELL timeout in seconds (0 = unlimited). Cleared by NEW.

CLI flags (set at startup, not runtime):
  --shell-timeout=N    : SYSTEM/SHELL timeout in seconds (0 = unlimited; default 300 in batch)
  --noshell            : Disable SYSTEM/SHELL; also disables -p
  --nosubmit           : Disable SUBMIT
  --ignore-math-errors : Domain errors return MISSING
  --clen <n>           : Set max character variable length
  -m <n>               : Set max in-memory table cells (rows*cols; 0 = unlimited)
  -t <n>               : Set max temporary variables
  -k                   : Continue execution after statement error
  -p <pager>           : External pager for interactive output
  -q                   : Quiet mode (suppress console output)
  -o <file>            : Redirect console output to file
  -u <fmt>             : Default input format (CSV/ODF/OOXML)
  -s <fmt>             : Default output format (CSV/ODF/OOXML)

Execution Tiers
sdata commands fall into three execution tiers:

  Declarative -- configure state for the next RUN.
    These commands take effect immediately but their primary
    action occurs when RUN is executed.
    Commands: USE, SAVE, BY, SELECT (filter), SELECT /ALL,
              REPEAT n, KEEP, DROP, FPATH

  Immediate -- execute at once, outside any data step.
    Commands: RUN, SORT, NEW, NAMES, LIST, DISPLAY, UNSET, RENAME,
              SYSTEM, SUBMIT, ECHO, DIGITS, RSEED, OUTPUT, HELP,
              DELETE n[-m], QUIT, END

  Deferred -- queued between RUN markers; executed once per
    record during the data step.
    Commands: LET, SET, PRINT, IF, FOR, WHILE, REPEAT/UNTIL,
              SELECT/CASE, DELETE, WRITE, HOLD, UNHOLD,
              ARRAY, DIM, BREAK

Note: SELECT has two forms with different tiers:
  SELECT <expr> / SELECT /ALL  -- Declarative (row filter)
  SELECT CASE ... END SELECT   -- Deferred (multi-way branch)

The HELP entry for each command includes an "Execution:" line
identifying which tier it belongs to.

Concepts: PDV, LET vs SET, and BY Groups

--- Program Data Vector (PDV) ---
A data step processes the table one record at a time.  For each record
sdata loads the source row into the PDV (Program Data Vector), executes
all deferred statements (LET, SET, IF, PRINT, ...), then writes the
result to the output table.

Each permanent variable (LET column) is reset to MISSING at the start of
every record before the source row is loaded.  HOLD retains a value
across records:
  HOLD RUNNING_TOT   -- carry RUNNING_TOT forward from the previous record

--- LET vs SET ---
Both assign values inside the data step, but their persistence differs:

  LET var = expr   Permanent column.  Written to the output table;
                   visible after RUN in DISPLAY, NAMES, and SAVE.
                   Reset to MISSING at the start of each record
                   unless retained by HOLD.

  SET var = expr   Session variable.  NOT written to the output table.
                   NOT reset between records or between RUN calls.
                   Persists until UNSET, NEW, or the session ends.
                   Use SET for counters and values that should not
                   appear as output columns.

A common mistake: using LET for a counter that should not appear as an
output column.  Use SET instead.

--- BY Groups ---
BY variable(s) partitions records into groups whose members share the same
values for the listed variables.  Records must already be in group order;
use SORT first if needed.  Bare BY (no variables) cancels grouping.

  BOG()   1 at the first record of each group, 0 otherwise
  EOG()   1 at the last record of each group, 0 otherwise

LAG and NEXT respect group boundaries: they return MISSING rather than
reading into an adjacent group.

Example -- subtotal SALARY by DEPT:
  SORT DEPT$
  BY DEPT$
  HOLD DEPT_TOT
  IF BOG() THEN SET DEPT_TOT = 0
  SET DEPT_TOT = DEPT_TOT + SALARY
  IF EOG() THEN PRINT DEPT$, DEPT_TOT
  RUN

See also: HELP LET  HELP SET  HELP BY  HELP HOLD  HELP EXECUTION

Debug mode: --debug[=N] flag  (N = 1, 2, or 3; default 3)
Enables trace output to stderr and interactive step mode.

Verbosity levels:
  1  sparse   I/O transitions only
  2  normal   Level 1 + per-record header + control-flow outcomes
  3  verbose  Level 2 + every LET/SET assignment

Level 1 trace events:
  [debug] USE: opened file.csv (N records, M variables)
  [debug] SUBMIT: entering script.sdata
  [debug] RUN complete: N records, M variables

Level 2 adds:
  [debug] -- record N (physical P)  [BY GROUP ...]
  [debug] IF -> TRUE / FALSE
  [debug] ELSE -> taken
  [debug] FOR I = 3
  [debug] SELECT -> KEPT / DROPPED
  [debug] SELECT -> N of M records kept
  [debug] DELETE: record marked

Level 3 adds:
  [debug] LET X = 5.00000         each scalar or array assignment
  [debug] SET X = 5.00000

Runtime control:  OPTIONS DEBUG N  (0 disables tracing)

Step mode (--debug[=N] + interactive stdin):
  After each record header, execution pauses at the inspection prompt.
  CONTINUE/C processes the current record and advances to the next.
  STEP/S is equivalent to CONTINUE in step mode.
  RUN at the prompt disables step mode and runs to completion.

The inspection prompt ([debug:record N]>) accepts the same commands as
BREAK: PRINT, RECORD, CONTINUE, STEP, RUN.  Record navigation at the
prompt does not affect which record is processed when execution resumes.

See also: HELP BREAK for the BREAK / BREAK WHEN deferred statement.

=== FUNCTION REFERENCE ===
Function: ABS(x)  ->  |x|

Function: SQRT(x) / SQR(x)  ->  square root of x (x >= 0)

Function: SGN(x)  ->  sign of x: -1, 0, or 1

Function: LOG(x)  ->  natural logarithm (x > 0)

Function: LOG10(x)  ->  base-10 logarithm (x > 0)

Function: EXP(x)  ->  e raised to the power x

Function: ROUND(x [, n])  ->  x rounded to n decimal places (default 0)

Function: CEIL(x)  ->  smallest integer >= x

Function: FLOOR(x)  ->  largest integer <= x

Function: INT(x)  ->  largest integer <= x (floor; rounds toward -infinity)

Function: FIX(x) / IP(x)  ->  integer part, truncated toward zero

Function: FP(x)  ->  fractional part: x - FIX(x)

Function: LN(x) / LOGE(x)  ->  natural logarithm (aliases for LOG; x > 0)

Function: LOG2(x)  ->  base-2 logarithm (x > 0)

Function: CLG(x) / LGT(x)  ->  common (base-10) logarithm (aliases for LOG10; x > 0)

Function: MOD(x, y)  ->  x mod y (floor division remainder)

Function: SIN(x)  ->  sine of x (radians)

Function: COS(x)  ->  cosine of x (radians)

Function: TAN(x)  ->  tangent of x (radians)

Function: ATN(x)  ->  arctangent of x (radians)

Function: ATAN2(y, x)  ->  arctangent of y/x (radians)

Function: ARCSIN(x)  ->  arcsine of x in radians (-1 <= x <= 1)

Function: ARCCOS(x)  ->  arccosine of x in radians (-1 <= x <= 1)

Function: ARCTAN(x) / ATN(x)  ->  arctangent of x in radians

Function: COT(x)  ->  cotangent of x (radians); cos(x)/sin(x)

Function: CSC(x)  ->  cosecant of x (radians); 1/sin(x)

Function: SEC(x)  ->  secant of x (radians); 1/cos(x)

Function: SINH(x) / HSN(x)  ->  hyperbolic sine

Function: COSH(x) / HCS(x)  ->  hyperbolic cosine

Function: TANH(x) / HTN(x)  ->  hyperbolic tangent

Function: DEG(x) / DEGREE(x)  ->  convert x from radians to degrees

Function: SIND(x)    ->  sine of x (degrees)

Function: COSD(x)    ->  cosine of x (degrees)

Function: TAND(x)    ->  tangent of x (degrees)

Function: ATND(x)    ->  arctangent of x (degrees)

Function: ATAN2D(y,x) ->  arctangent of y/x (degrees)

Function: LEN(s$)  ->  length of string s$

Function: LEFT$(s$, n)  ->  leftmost n characters

Function: RIGHT$(s$, n)  ->  rightmost n characters

Function: MID$(s$, start [, len])  ->  substring

Function: SEG$(s$, start, len)  ->  substring (start 0=1; len > 0 required)

Function: TRIM$(s$)  ->  strip leading and trailing spaces

Function: LTRIM$(s$)  ->  strip leading spaces

Function: RTRIM$(s$)  ->  strip trailing spaces

Function: UCASE$(s$) / UPPER$(s$)  ->  convert to upper case

Function: LCASE$(s$) / LOWER$(s$)  ->  convert to lower case

Function: POS(needle$, haystack$)  ->  1-based position, 0=not found

Function: INSTR(haystack$, needle$)  ->  1-based position, 0=not found (BW BASIC argument order)

Function: CHR$(n)  ->  character with ASCII code n

Function: ASCII(s$) / ASC(s$)  ->  ASCII code of first character of s$

Function: STR$(x)  ->  numeric x formatted as string

Function: VAL(s$)  ->  parse string s$ as a number

Function: NUM$(x)  ->  numeric x formatted as string (alias for STR$)

Function: NUM(x)  ->  convert string or integer x to float

Function: HEX$(n)  ->  hexadecimal string for integer n

Function: HEX(s$)  ->  integer value of hexadecimal string s$

Function: OCT$(n)  ->  octal string for integer n

Function: BIN$(n)  ->  binary string for integer n

Function: RECNO()  ->  current logical record number (1-based)
  When a SELECT filter is active, RECNO counts only visible records.

Function: BOF()  ->  1 if this is the first visible record, else 0
  Respects any active SELECT filter (logical first record).

Function: EOF()  ->  1 if this is the last visible record, else 0
  Respects any active SELECT filter (logical last record).

Function: BOG()  ->  1 at the start of a BY group, else 0
  Operates in logical space; filtered-out records are invisible.

Function: EOG()  ->  1 at the end of a BY group, else 0
  Operates in logical space; filtered-out records are invisible.

Function: LAG("varname" [, n]) / LAGC$("varname" [, n])
Returns the value of the named variable n records back (default n=1).
Returns missing at the start of the dataset or at a BY-group boundary.
When a SELECT filter is active, only visible (logical) records are counted;
filtered-out rows are completely invisible to LAG.
The variable name may be given unquoted: LAG(X) is equivalent to LAG("X").
LAG returns a numeric value; LAGC$ returns a string value.

Function: NEXT("varname" [, n]) / NEXTC$("varname" [, n])
Returns the value of the named variable n records ahead (default n=1).
Returns missing at the end of the dataset or at a BY-group boundary.
When a SELECT filter is active, only visible (logical) records are counted;
filtered-out rows are completely invisible to NEXT.
The variable name may be given unquoted: NEXT(X) is equivalent to NEXT("X").
NEXT returns a numeric value; NEXTC$ returns a string value.

Function: OBS("varname", row) / OBSC$("varname", row)
Returns the value of the named variable from the specified physical row.
row: 1-based row index in the Data Table, counting all rows regardless of
any active SELECT filter (i.e. OBS ignores the logical/filtered view).
Returns missing if row < 1 or row > total row count.
The variable name may be given unquoted: OBS(X, 3) is equivalent to OBS("X", 3).
OBS returns a numeric value; OBSC$ returns a string value.

Function: MISSING(x)  ->  1 if x is missing, else 0

Function: INF(x)  ->  1 if x is +Inf or -Inf, else 0
  Returns 0 for finite numeric values, missing values, and strings.

  To test for positive infinity:  INF(x) AND x > 0
  To test for negative infinity:  INF(x) AND x < 0
  NOT INF(x) serves the role of FINITE() for non-missing values.

  Inf arises from arithmetic overflow (MAXNUM() * 2.0) or from
  float division by zero when OPTIONS IEEE_DIVIDE YES is set.
  See also: MISSING, OPTIONS IEEE_DIVIDE

Function: RAN() / RANDOM() / RND()  ->  uniform random number in [0, 1)
  Use RSEED n before calling to get a reproducible sequence.

Function: DATE$()  ->  current date as "YYYY-MM-DD"

Function: TIME$()  ->  current time as "HH:MM:SS"

Function: SHELL("command")  ->  0 on success, 1 on failure
  Disabled by --noshell flag.

Function: FALSE  ->  0 (numeric false constant)

Function: TRUE   ->  1 (numeric true constant)

Function: ERR()  ->  last error code (0 = no error, 1 = error caught)
  Set when an error is caught by -k (--continue-on-error).
  Not set by --ignore-math-errors domain warnings.
  Reset to 0 by the NEW command.

Function: ERL()  ->  record number where the last caught error occurred
  Returns 0 if no error has been caught in the current session.
  Set alongside ERR() when -k catches a runtime error.
  Reset to 0 by the NEW command.

Function: SUM(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the sum of non-missing values across the arguments.
Missing values are skipped; SUM of all-missing arguments returns 0.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: MEAN(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the arithmetic mean of non-missing values across the arguments.
Missing values are excluded; the divisor is the non-missing count.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: GMEAN(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the geometric mean of non-missing values across the arguments.
Returns missing if any argument is <= 0 or all arguments are missing.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: HMEAN(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the harmonic mean of non-missing values across the arguments.
Returns missing if any argument is zero or all arguments are missing.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: STD(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the sample standard deviation (n-1 denominator) of non-missing values.
Returns missing when fewer than 2 non-missing values are supplied.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: VAR(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the sample variance (n-1 denominator) of non-missing values.
Returns missing when fewer than 2 non-missing values are supplied.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: MIN(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the smallest non-missing value across the arguments.
Returns missing if all arguments are missing.

Function: MAX(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the largest non-missing value across the arguments.
Returns missing if all arguments are missing.

Function: MEDIAN(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the median of non-missing values across the arguments.
Values are sorted internally; missing values are excluded.
Returns missing if all arguments are missing.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: N(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the count of non-missing values across the supplied arguments.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Function: NMISS(v1 [, v2, ...])
Returns the count of missing values across the supplied arguments.
Arguments may be individual values or array names (expanded automatically).

Statistical distribution functions follow a uniform naming convention.

Function suffix meanings:
  DF   Probability density function (PDF) or probability mass (PMF)
  CF   Cumulative distribution function: P(X <= x)
  IF   Inverse CDF (quantile): value x such that P(X <= x) = p  (0 < p < 1)
  RN   Generate a random variate from the distribution

Common argument names:
  x      Continuous variate value
  k      Discrete variate value (non-negative integer)
  p      Probability for inverse CDF  (0 < p < 1)

Distribution prefixes:
  Z  Standard Normal (fixed mu=0, sigma=1)
  N  Binomial  (n trials, prob success probability)
  U  Uniform on [lo, hi]
  E  Exponential with rate parameter
  B  Beta  (shape parameters a, b)
  P  Poisson  (mean lambda)
  G  Gamma  (shape, rate)
  X  Chi-square  (df degrees of freedom)
  T  Student's t  (df degrees of freedom)
  F  F distribution  (df1, df2 degrees of freedom)
  M  Binomial  (n trials, prob success probability)
  W  Weibull  (scale, shape)
  L  Laplace / double-exponential  (loc, scale)

Use HELP <prefix>DF for full details on each family.

Normal distribution (mu and sigma are optional; default mu=0, sigma=1):
  ZDF(x [, mu, sigma])   probability density at x
  ZCF(x [, mu, sigma])   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  ZIF(p [, mu, sigma])   quantile: x such that P(X <= x) = p  (0 < p < 1)
  ZRN([mu, sigma])       random variate

Binomial distribution (discrete):
  NDF(k, n, prob)   probability mass P(X = k)  (k = 0, 1, ..., n)
  NCF(k, n, prob)   cumulative probability P(X <= k)
  NIF(p, n, prob)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  NRN(n, prob)      random variate
  n: number of trials (positive integer)
  prob: success probability per trial (0 <= prob <= 1)
See also: MDF/MCF/MIF/MRN (identical functions, alternative prefix).

Uniform distribution on [lo, hi]:
  UDF(x, lo, hi)   probability density (1/(hi-lo) for lo <= x <= hi)
  UCF(x, lo, hi)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  UIF(p, lo, hi)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  URN(lo, hi)      random variate on [lo, hi]
  URN()            random variate on [0, 1] (default bounds)
  lo, hi: interval bounds (lo < hi)

Exponential distribution:
  EDF(x, rate)   probability density (rate*exp(-rate*x), x >= 0)
  ECF(x, rate)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  EIF(p, rate)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  ERN(rate)      random variate
  rate: rate parameter lambda (rate > 0); mean = 1/rate

Beta distribution on [0, 1]:
  BDF(x, a, b)   probability density
  BCF(x, a, b)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  BIF(p, a, b)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  BRN(a, b)      random variate
  a, b: shape parameters (both > 0)

Poisson distribution (discrete):
  PDF(k, lambda)   probability mass P(X = k)  (k non-negative integer)
  PCF(k, lambda)   cumulative probability P(X <= k)
  PIF(p, lambda)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  PRN(lambda)      random variate
  lambda: mean arrival rate (lambda > 0)

Gamma distribution:
  GDF(x, shape, rate)   probability density (x >= 0)
  GCF(x, shape, rate)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  GIF(p, shape, rate)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  GRN(shape, rate)      random variate
  shape: shape parameter k (> 0); rate: rate parameter (> 0)
  mean = shape/rate;  variance = shape/rate^2

Chi-square distribution:
  XDF(x, df)   probability density (x >= 0)
  XCF(x, df)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  XIF(p, df)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  XRN(df)      random variate
  df: degrees of freedom (positive integer)
  mean = df;  variance = 2*df

Student's t distribution:
  TDF(x, df)   probability density
  TCF(x, df)   cumulative probability P(T <= x)
  TIF(p, df)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  TRN(df)      random variate
  df: degrees of freedom (df > 0; need not be an integer)

F distribution:
  FDF(x, df1, df2)   probability density (x >= 0)
  FCF(x, df1, df2)   cumulative probability P(F <= x)
  FIF(p, df1, df2)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  FRN(df1, df2)      random variate
  df1: numerator degrees of freedom; df2: denominator degrees of freedom
  (both > 0; need not be integers)

Binomial distribution (discrete):
  MDF(k, n, prob)   probability mass P(X = k)  (k = 0, 1, ..., n)
  MCF(k, n, prob)   cumulative probability P(X <= k)
  MIF(p, n, prob)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  MRN(n, prob)      random variate
  n: number of trials (positive integer)
  prob: success probability per trial (0 <= prob <= 1)
See also: NDF/NCF/NIF/NRN (identical functions, alternative prefix).

Weibull distribution:
  WDF(x, scale, shape)   probability density (x >= 0)
  WCF(x, scale, shape)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  WIF(p, scale, shape)   quantile  (0 < p < 1)
  WRN(scale, shape)      random variate
  scale: scale parameter lambda (> 0); shape: shape parameter k (> 0)
  Exponential is the special case shape = 1.

Logistic distribution (standard, location=0, scale=1):
  LDF(x)   probability density at x
  LCF(x)   cumulative probability P(X <= x)
  LIF(p)   quantile / inverse CDF  (0 < p < 1)
  LRN      random variate

